<big><b>Countable and Uncountable Nouns</b></big>

<big><b>COUNTABLE AND UNCOUNTABLE NOUNS</b></big>

Nouns in English can be divided into two groups:

• Countable Nouns
• Uncountable Nouns

Understanding the difference helps us use articles, quantifiers, and verbs correctly.


<big><b>Countable Nouns</b></big>

Countable nouns are things that can be counted individually.

They have singular and plural forms.

Examples:

• Book → Books
• Apple → Apples
• Student → Students
• Car → Cars

We can use:

• A / An
• Many
• Few
• Several

Examples:

• I have <b>a book</b>.
• She bought <b>many apples</b>.
• There are <b>several students</b> in the classroom.
• Only a <b>few cars</b> were parked outside.


<big><b>Uncountable Nouns</b></big>

Uncountable nouns are things that cannot usually be counted individually.

They normally do not have a plural form.

Examples:

• Water
• Milk
• Sugar
• Information
• Money

We can use:

• Much
• Little
• Some
• A lot of

Examples:

• There is <b>some water</b> in the bottle.
• We need <b>more information</b>.
• She has <b>a lot of money</b>.
• There is very <b>little sugar</b> left.


<big><b>Words Used with Countable Nouns</b></big>

Some words are commonly used only with countable nouns.

Examples:

• Many books
• Few students
• Several houses
• A number of cars

Examples in sentences:

• Many people attended the event.
• Few students passed the difficult test.
• Several houses were damaged by the storm.


<big><b>Words Used with Uncountable Nouns</b></big>

Some words are commonly used only with uncountable nouns.

Examples:

• Much water
• Little time
• Some milk
• A lot of information

Examples in sentences:

• We do not have much time.
• There is little milk in the fridge.
• She gave us some useful information.


<big><b>Common Mistakes</b></big>

Some nouns are uncountable in English even if they may be countable in other languages.

Examples:

• Information ✓
• Informations ✗

• Advice ✓
• Advices ✗

• Furniture ✓
• Furnitures ✗

Correct sentences:

• She gave me good advice.
• We received useful information.
• The furniture is expensive.


<big><b>Quick Comparison</b></big>

Countable Nouns:

• One apple
• Two apples
• Many apples
• Few apples

Uncountable Nouns:

• Water
• Much water
• Little water
• Some water


<big><b>Remember</b></big>

• Use <b>many</b> with countable nouns.
• Use <b>much</b> with uncountable nouns.
• Countable nouns have singular and plural forms.
• Uncountable nouns usually do not have plural forms.


